    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Gigartina stiriata</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_7933",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Gametophyte thick, fleshy and succulent-like, main blades covered with numerous large, freshy papillae arranged in irregular rows. Sporophyte also thick, but with a forked blade that is spotted with dark spore-bearing tissue. Colour yellowish-brown.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_7934",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Blades up to about 300 mm tall, but more typically about 100 mm.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_7935",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Southern African and Tristan da Cunha.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u><i> </i>Namibia to Cape Agulhas.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_7936",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Very distinctive species found on intertidal rocks in the mid- to low shore, where it is often found adjacent to the more dominant <i>Gigartina polycarpa</i>.</p><p>Has potential as a source for the extraction of carrageenan, a chemical used in the food industry as a gelling and thickening agent.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_7937",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_7938",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>The forked sporophyte phase and distinctive gametophyte are similar in size and often found adjacently.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_7939",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The fleshy succulent-like shape of the gametophyte, with its large rows of fleshy papillae, is unmistakable and distinguishes this from local <i>Gigartina</i> species.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_7940",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa (Fourth edition). Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 398). <br><br>Hughey, J, Silva, P & Hommersand, M (2002). ITS1 sequences of type specimens of <i>Gigartina</i> and <i>Sarcothalia</i> and their significance for the classification of South African Gigartinaceae (Gigartinales, Rhodophyta). <i>European Journal of Phycology</i>, 37(2), 209-216.<br><br>Stegenga, H, Bolton, J & Anderson, R (1997). Seaweeds of the South African west coast. <i>Contributions of the Bolus Herbarium</i>, 18. (p. 352, as <i>Gigartina stiriata</i>).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_7941",
            "longText": null,
